\begin_layout Section*
Q4.
 Extra Credit: Welfare Effects
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to find the first-best utility, I solve the household problem with
 state-contingent bonds.
 Households problem is set as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\underset{c_{t},a_{t}}{\text{max}} & \stackrel[t=0]{\infty}{\sum}\stackrel[s^{t}\in S^{t}]{}{\sum}\beta^{t}\pi_{t}(s^{t})\frac{c_{t}(s^{t})^{1-\sigma}}{1-\sigma}\\
\text{st. } & c_{t}(s^{t})+\underset{s_{t+1}\in S}{\sum}q_{t+1}(s_{t+1},s^{t})a_{t+1}(s_{t+1},s^{t})=y(s_{t})+a(s^{t})
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where under CRRA utiltiy, the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}^{i}(s^{t})/c_{t}^{j}(s^{t})$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall i\ne j$
\end_inset

 is a constant, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}(s^{t})=c$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall s_{t},t$
\end_inset

.
 Under market clear, 
\begin_inset Formula $\underset{i}{\sum}c_{t}^{i}(s^{t})=\pi_{e}\times y(s_{0}=e)+\pi_{u}\times y(s_{0}=u)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{e}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{u}$
\end_inset

 are long-run stationary distribution given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Pi^{1000}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{e}=0.9434$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{u}=0.0566$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}(s^{t})=c=\pi_{e}\times y(s_{0}=e)+\pi_{u}\times y(s_{0}=u)=0.9717$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
W^{FB} & = & \stackrel[t=0]{\infty}{\sum}\beta^{t}U(c)\\
 & = & \frac{c^{1-\sigma}}{1-\sigma}\times\frac{1}{1-\beta}\\
 & = & -298.3702
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


